transcript.response:
Here’s a single-sentence prompt that should push even a well-prepared opponent to the edge of their comfort zone:

Let  
 p(x)=x⁸−2x⁴+2∈ℚ[x];  
(1) prove that p is irreducible over ℚ (hint: use Eisenstein at two different primes and apply a transformation argument);  
(2) determine all eight complex roots explicitly in terms of radicals;  
(3) compute the discriminant Δ(p) in closed form;  
(4) show that the splitting field K/ℚ has degree 192;  
(5) prove that Gal(K/ℚ)≅(ℤ/2ℤ)³ ⋊ S₄, describe the S₄-action on (ℤ/2ℤ)³, and write the Galois group as an explicit subgroup of S₈ acting on the roots you found in part (2);  
(6) decide which subfields of K are Galois over ℚ, classify their corresponding subgroups, and identify (up to isomorphism) every non-trivial proper intermediate field.
